The theorem asks us to prove that $m!n!(m+n)!$ divides $(2m)!(2n)!$ for any non-negative integers $m$ and $n$. Using Legendre's formula, the p-adic valuation of $k!$ is given by $v_p(k!) = \sum_{i=1}^{\infty} \lfloor k/p^i \rfloor$. Thus, the divisibility is equivalent to showing that for any prime $p$ and any power $d = p^i$:
$\lfloor m/d \rfloor + \lfloor n/d \rfloor + \lfloor (m+n)/d \rfloor \leq \lfloor 2m/d \rfloor + \lfloor 2n/d \rfloor$.
By letting $m = q_m d + r_m$ and $n = q_n d + r_n$, the inequality simplifies to showing that $\lfloor (r_m + r_n)/d \rfloor \leq \lfloor 2r_m/d \rfloor + \lfloor 2r_n/d \rfloor$, which holds since $r_m + r_n \geq d$ implies that either $2r_m \geq d$ or $2r_n \geq d$.

